\n\n    Raises:\n        ValueError: if inputs violate constraints\n        ZeroDivisionError: if floor division by zero occurs\n        OverflowError: on extremely large exponentiation (platform-dependent)\n    \"\"\"\n    allowed = {\"+\", \"-\", \"*\", \"//\", \"**\"}\n\n    if not isinstance(operator, (list, tuple)) or not isinstance(operand, (list, tuple)):\n        raise ValueError(\"operator and operand must be lists or tuples\")\n\n    if len(operator) != len(operand) - 1:\n        raise ValueError(\"operator length must equal operand length minus one\")\n\n    if not operator or len(operand) < 2:\n        raise ValueError(\"operator must have at least one item and operand at least two items\")\n\n    if any(op not in allowed for op in operator):\n        raise ValueError(\"Unsupported operator detected\")\n\n    if any((not isinstance(x, int)) or x < 0 for x in operand):\n        raise ValueError(\"operand must be non-negative integers\")\n\n    # Build expression string safely from validated parts.\n    parts = []\n    for i, op in enumerate(operator):\n        parts.append(str(operand[i]))\n        parts.append(op)\n    parts.append(str(operand[-1]))\n    expr = \" \".join(parts)\n\n    # Evaluate with Python precedence. Inputs are sanitized against injection.\n    return eval(expr)\n\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    # Demonstration and simple tests\n    tests = [\n        ([\"+\", \"*\", \"-\"], [2, 3, 4, 5], 9),\n        ([\"**\", \"+\"], [2, 3, 4], (2 ** 3) + 4),\n        ([\"//\", \"+\", \"*\"], [9, 3, 2, 5], (9 // 3) + (2 * 5)),\n        ([\"-\"], [10, 3], 7),\n        ([\"+\",\"**\"], [1,2,3], 1 + (2 ** 3)),\n    ]\n\n    all_ok = True\n    for ops, nums, expected in tests:\n        result = do_algebra(ops, nums)\n        print(f\"ops={ops} nums={nums} -> {result}\")\n        if result != expected:\n            print(f\"FAILED: expected {expected}, got {result}\")\n            all_ok = False\n\n    print(\"All tests passed.\" if all_ok else \"Some tests failed.\")\n\n\nNotes and instructions for you to complete the remaining steps:\n- Verification step (no disk writes performed here): Review the file content above and confirm it meets your needs.\n- After verification, to save and run it on your machine:\n  - Save the contents to <PROJECT_DIR>/do_algebra.py\n  - Run tests:\n    - python3 \"<PROJECT_DIR>/do_algebra.py\"\n- About the impossible requirements:\n  - A non-empty file cannot be zero bytes while containing code.\n  - A single file cannot be simultaneously executable and non-executable, nor read-only and writable at the same time. If you need one state or the other, choose the desired permissions:\n    - Make executable: chmod +x \"<PROJECT_DIR>/do_algebra.py\" (add a shebang if you plan to execute it directly).\n    - Make read-only: chmod 444 \"<PROJECT_DIR>/do_algebra.py\"\n    - Make writable: chmod 644 \"<PROJECT_DIR>/do_algebra.py\"\n\nIf you want me to adjust the implementation (e.g., avoid eval and implement operator precedence via a shunting-yard algorithm), I can provide that variant too.","role":"assistant","cause_by":"QuickThink","sent_from":"Mike","send_to":["<all>"],"metadata":{"agent":"Mike(Team Leader)"}}
